item.title: [DATACMNS-685] ConversionMatchAbbreviationException being thrown from ToEntityConverter.matches(…)
item.description:

status.description: The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are not closed can be reopened.

comments.comment: I have created a sample repository that reproduces the problem: https://github.com/paranoiabla/DATACMNS-685

I believe this is because the `UriToEntityConverter` is created only for the domainClass and not for the `alternativeDomainTypes`. Is this correct? Can we have the converter registered also for the `alternativeDomainTypes`?

OK, we made some progress on this issue and we believe what's happening is the following:

  • RepositorySearchController:executeSearch is being called
  • that one calls RepositorySearchController:executeQueryMethod which calls the prepareUris method.
  • and from there the UriToEntityConverter is called. However when the UriToEntityConverter is being created inside it's constructor an object PersistentEntities entities is being passed and this object does not contain the alternativeDomainTypes. It only contains the domainTypes.

To overcome the problem we have created our own implementation of UriToEntityConverter and we overwrote the constructor (to me it seems wrong to put your logic in a constructor, but that's another topic) like this:

    public NemesisUriToEntityConverter(Repositories repositories, ConversionService conversionService) {
 
        super(new PersistentEntities(Collections.emptyList()), conversionService);
 
        ........
 
    }

This seems to work fine because our repository objects are working against the alternativeDomainTypes.

This should be fixed in master and the maintenance branches. Regarding the UriToEntityConverter I think that's an orthogonal topic and not easily solvable as the interfaces can't be added to the PersistentEntities easily: it's not clear which store they actually belong to, which means it's unclear which MappingContext they should be added to. The JpaMetamodelMappingContext is not really suitable here as the types aren't actually JPA managed.
